<HEADLINE> France Urges All Zairian Leaders to Hold Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- France today called on all the
"Zairian leaders" to hold dialogue with each other in order to
"save your country" and organize free elections.
</P>
<P>
"We say to all the Zairian leaders: hold dialogue, renounce
hostilities, resume negotiations with the assistance of the
special representatives of the United Nations secretary general
and the OAU (Organization of African Unity). Save your country,
lead it to free and democratic elections. There is no other
political way," said a spokesman of the French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that France is following "with the greatest
attention all the taking of positions by everybody, no matter
whether he is (one of) the government personalities or those of
the AFDL (Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Congo-Zaire)."
</P>
<P>
AFDL leader Laurent-Desire Kabila said Friday that France has
become "reasonable" in its attitude toward the AFDL.
</P>
<P>
"It (France) is no more what it was at the beginning. It
becomes reasonable. There is less aggressiveness toward us," said
Kabila in an interview with the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko today rejected
the ultimatum by Kabila asking him to talk with the rebels within
three days, but said that he would negotiate with the latter if he
"asks for it politely."
</P>
<P>
"I am a chief of state. I am not to receive ultimatum from the
chiefs of bands," said Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
He said that he "cannot refuse to talk to a Zairian compatriot"
if he asks for it politely.
</P>
<P>
"But being in Goma (eastern Zaire) and say that I give three
days if he does not answer, this is not my style. It is not in my
nature and I cannot answer.... If they say, Mr. President of the
Republic of Zaire, my intention is to meet you, this is polite,"
said Mobutu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
