<HEADLINE> European Parliament Votes on EU Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament has
lately narrowly approved a report criticizing the European Union's
human rights record, with the legislature's leftist and righting
parties squaring off over individual liberties.
</P>
<P>
The parliament approved the document presented by its Committee
on Civil Liberties and Internal Affairs by a vote of 174 to 166,
with 66 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The report offered a broad range of issues to be included under
the umbrella of human rights -- opposition to euthanasia, the
right to a clean environment, and the need to safeguard personal
information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Among the alleged human rights deficiencies cited are the use
of euthanasia in the Netherlands, the export of arms by Germany to
Turkey, and the imprisonment by Greece of conscientious objectors
to military service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
