<HEADLINE> Chang Faces Rafter in Hong Kong Open Tennis Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Michael Chang beat
Sweden's fourth seed Thomas Johansson in the semi-finals, and the
Chinese-American is only one step away from his third title at
the Salem Open Tennis tournament here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chang, winner of the Hong Kong Open in 1994 and 1995 and
runner-up to Pete Sampras last year, outplayed Johansson 7-6
(7-5), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Chang will meet Australia's fifth-seeded Patrick Rafter in a
repeat of the 1994 final. Rafter won the semi-final match after
308th-ranked American qualifier Brian MacPhie was forced to retire
with an upper arm injury when trailing 3-6, 6-1, 3-0 in the other
semifinal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"In the first set we both struggled on our first serve but
after that I settled down and served a lot better," said Chang,
who is local fans' hero.
</P>
<P>
"I am excited to be in the final in Hong Kong where I have such
dedicated fans," he continued.
</P>
<P>
But he is not optimistic of the final slated for Sunday
afternoon. "It will be a tough game," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Rafter was more worried of about he would make the same mistake
as on the eve of the 1994 final. He had some seafood before the
title match and then suffered from food poisoning during the
match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
