<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM to Tout Big Projects on Asian Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
Ganzouri said today that he will embark on a 10-day tour of
Singapore, Malaysia and China Sunday in a bid to attract
investment for Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri today reviewed the projects Egypt wants to establish
in cooperation with the three booming economies in the Far East at
an intensive pre-departure meeting with his delegation, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian side will present a number of joint ventures for
the development of southern Egypt and implementing infrastructure
of giant national projects, including setting up a free industrial
and trade zone in the Suez Canal area, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will also brief their Asian counterparts on
the investment opportunities in various areas in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also presented to President Hosni Mubarak the
agreements to be signed during the trip, four with Malaysia, and
five with Singapore and China.
</P>
<P>
The agreements provide for protection of investments,
prevention of dual taxation, activation of trade movement and
implementation of joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The premier said he expects Egypt to set up six joint projects
with Singapore in various fields and form a free trade zone east
of Suez Canal with Malaysia, he added.
</P>
<P>
For days, local press has shed spotlight on the tour, which
acquires special importance as the first ever visit by an Egyptian
prime minister to those countries since 1964.
</P>
<P>
Egypt attaches extra interest to the tour also because of its
keenness to link its economy with that of other states that enjoy
high growth rates to benefit from their experiments, said MENA.
</P>
<P>
Thus his talks in these countries will focus on available
investment opportunities as well as ways to enhance Egypt's
relations with them.
</P>
<P>
Talks in Malaysia, a member of the Association of South East
Asian Nations (ASEAN), will dwell on ways to encourage investment
in Egypt and improve trade balance between the two countries
tilting in favor of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, Ganzouri will explore ways to increase trade
exchange which stood at about 211 million U.S. dollars during
the first 10 months last year.
</P>
<P>
In China, the prime minister will seek opportunities on joint
projects on energy, industry and investment, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will be accompanied by a high-level
delegation grouping the ministers of electricity, trade, industry,
local administration and cabinet affairs along with a team of
investors and businessmen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
