<HEADLINE> World Bank Loan Ready for Disbursement in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The 63.6-million-U.S.-Dollar
World Bank loan facility for Zimbabwe's small-and-medium scale
businesses will be released next week, a deputy minister said
today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Industry and Commerce Obert Mpofu said
eight financial institutions have now been designated to disburse
the funds under the enterprise development facility.
</P>
<P>
The loan facility was a result of a development credit
agreement negotiated between the government and the International
Development Association (IDA), he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the IDA lent Zimbabwe the loan at a
standard variable interest rate of 0.75 percent with a maturity
of forty years, including ten years grace period.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to support a more broad based but rapid
growth of the private sector including enterprises whose growth
is contingent on direct or indirect expansion of non-traditional
exports.
</P>
<P>
"Under the facility, the maximum amount that enterprises can
borrow is the equivalent of 75,000 U.S. Dollars," said Mpofu.
</P>
</TEXT>
