<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Foreign Minister to Visit Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Yiannakis Cassoulides will visit Athens next week for talks with
the Greek leaders on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Greek Deputy Foreign Minister
Yiannos Kranidiotis, who is on a four-day working visit here,
after a meeting with Cassoulides who replaced Alecos Michaelides
in last Monday's cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis told reporters that he discussed with the Cypriot
Foreign Minister on Cyprus prospects for accession to the
European Union and the ongoing U.N.-sponsored proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the next two to three years will be
crucial to the Cyprus problem in relation to the island's EU
accession course.
</P>
<P>
"We don't foresee an easy road, there will be difficulties,
but I believe that there will also be opportunities," the
Greek official said, stressing that those opportunities must be
taken advantage of through a long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis also said a Cyprus solution must be based on
the 1977 and 1979 High Level Agreements the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides have signed, and relevant U.N. Security Council
Resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The High Level Agreements provide for a bizonal, bicommunal
federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
Friday, the Greek official has expressed his support to the
ongoing U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides, and hoped that the talks will be fruitful and
lead to direct talks between the two community leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the 37 percent of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.  
</P>
</TEXT>
