<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: EU Decides to Punish Iran in Non-US Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- European governments today began
the formal recall of ambassadors from Iran but showed that Europe
was not following the footsteps of the United States to isolate
the Islamic nation diplomatically and economically.
</P>
<P>
The fact that France has turned down the possibility of
economic sanctions on Tehran, indicated that the 15-nation
European Union was unlikely to go beyond the suspension of its
so-called critical dialogue with Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, Washington has been easily satisfied by the EU's
positive response to a German court ruling that Iran engaged in
state-run terrorism by slaying three Kurdish dissidents and their
translator in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 protestors, who have been angered by the ruling,
marched on the Germany embassy in Tehran, shouting slogans like
"Death to Germany" and "Fascist Germany" and throwing tomatoes at
the embassy residence.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani said that what has
happened, including the European action and the German ruling, was
something instigated by the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The optimistic president said that European ambassadors would
return to Iran soon since they did the same after protesting the
death edict against Salman Rushdie, the British author, in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Another reason Rafsanjani cited was the fact that Iran was a
stronger economy than eight years ago, which meant that its
economic charm could be used to balance the pressure from foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
While Tehran is condemning the German court ruling, Washington
hailed it as a recognition of U.S. charges that Iran sponsors
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Michael MuCurry said, "The European Union
and the German government responded appropriately to that court
decision." The U.S. would continue close consultations with the EU
about any "reprehensible" activity by Iran, he added.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, however, vowed to enhance
cooperation with Iran at a meeting in Moscow with the leader of
the Iranian Parliament, Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Gennadi Seleznyov, leader of the Communists in the Russian
Parliament, also expressed his sympathy with Iran, saying, "No
court in this world has the authority to pass sentence on a whole
country."
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that this different reaction from Moscow has shown
its determination to seek allies to support its opposition to the
planned expansion of NATO into Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
But the policy makers of EU nations are also no fools. They
know clearly that any commercial and diplomatic gap, which will be
left by any of the steps they are possibly going to take, will be
filled immediately by some of their eager neighbors.
</P>
<P>
And Iran, a country with a population of 65 million and rich
natural resources such as oil and gas, is not a geopolitical unit
which can be so easily ignored, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Rummelhardt, a spokesman for the French Foreign
Ministry, said that France would oppose any attempt to impose
economic sanctions against Iran.
</P>
<P>
He explained that economic sanctions were not an "appropriate"
solution to the issue in question.
</P>
<P>
Greece went even further by saying that it did not see the
necessity of recalling its ambassador.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, European oil companies said that they would
not withdraw their new investments in Iran.
</P>
<P>
But a senior EU official said that some sanctions, possibly
including a ban on visas for Iranian officials and restrictions on
loans to Tehran, would be among the options put to EU foreign
ministers when they meet on April 19 in Luxembourg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
