<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Builds First Nuclear Reactor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's first nuclear reactor,
which will begin operation at the end of 1997, is already under
construction, according to the latest issue of Al Ahram weekly.
</P>
<P>
The 22-megawatt reactor, to be used for peaceful purposes, is
being built in Argentina and will be installed in Inshass,
northeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Egypt imported two mini-reactors, two megawatts each, in the
1960s, it said.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the reactor will cost 350 million Egyptian
pounds (about 103 million U.S. dollars), with an additional 100
million pounds (29.4 million dollars) on purchasing a cyclotron to
produce radioactive isotopes.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Electricity and Energy Maher Abaza said that the
reactor would be used for "peaceful research in the fields of
agriculture, industry and medicine."
</P>
<P>
Egypt is a signatory of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and
another treaty banning nuclear tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Angolan People Hail Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- From the western coastal cities
to the eastern remote areas, festivals have been staged by
Angolans to hail peace dawning on the war-torn southern African
country at last.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola
(PMLA) and the former rebel movement, the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), joined hands to form a
government of national unity and reconciliation on Friday, a
development that marked a major victory in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In capital Luanda, a grand ceremony was held to mark the
swearing in of the unity government, attended by officials of the
newly-established governments, 13 foreign heads of state,
delegates of foreign governments, foreign envoys as well as tens
of thousands of Luandan citizens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local residents weary of war took to the major
streets leading to the city center where a parade of cars,
motors, bicycles was staged to hail the delayed peace.
</P>
<P>
In Kuito, capital of the central war-ravaged Bie Province,
local citizens started their procession in early morning, holding
placards and slogans reading "We want peace", "Rebuild Angola".
</P>
<P>
"Nobody in this country know better the misery of war and the
happiness of peace than we do," said a woman taking part in the
parade.
</P>
<P>
They still remember that at the end of 1992 when war broke out
again in Angola, about 50,000 people were killed in a single
fighting between the government troops and the former UNITA
rebels in Kuito. And the city itself was ravaged.
</P>
<P>
"The shadow of war is still haunting everybody who survives,"
said a local resident.
</P>
<P>
In the southern Huila Province, the central Kuanza-Norte
Province, the southwestern Cunene Province and the northeastern
Lunda-Sul Province, all kinds of festivities were held to
welcome a new stage of peaceful life.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old civil war, starting from 1975, killed at least
one million people, produced three million war refugees and
deprived 100,000 children of their parents.
</P>
<P>
The national economy was savagely ravaged with direct
financial loss reaching nearly 30 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
But now, with the establishment of the unity government,
despite many difficulties lying ahead, the Angolan people will
surely rebuild a new, prosperous Angola as they march toward a
lasting peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
