<HEADLINE> Egypt Blasts Israel's Refusal of EU Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today blasted Israel's refusal of a new European initiative
to resume the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The European logic include positive ideas and for this the
Israeli Prime Minister turned them down," he told reporters,
countering Binyamin Netanyahu's charge that the European Union is
biased toward the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli refusal is part of the negative stance," he said,
warning that the peace process will be ruined if Israel goes on
with its current policy.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting reports that 90 percent of the EU initiative on the
peace process are U.S. ideas, Moussa said they are "European
ones" and urged a more active European role.
</P>
<P>
He said the Europeans should work with the U.S. and other
parties in order to protect the peace process, which came to a
halt last month since Israel began to build a new Jewish
settlement on the edge of Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As the EU stepped up pressure for a greater say in the Mideast
peace-making, Netanyahu said the U.S. should be the center of
facilitating talks, warning that "too many cooks spoil the broth."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, currently on a four-day visit to the Netherlands
and Italy, has demanded the 15-nation bloc to create a "more
even-handed policy" and "more realistic expectations" about its
role to gap the differences between Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the Israeli leader, however, the Egyptian top
diplomat said the initiative is not perfect but it was clear that
the Europeans have thoroughly discussed the issue of settlement
and confidence re-building.
</P>
<P>
"Of course the European initiative does not reflect the Arab
stance. In the Arab logic, we will find that it needs some
amendments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt will take some diplomatic steps to protect
the peace drive and bring it back on track, based on the
land-for-peace principle and the need to halt settlements and
safeguard Jerusalem, a holy city to Muslims, Christians and Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
