<HEADLINE> Iran Stops Buying Meat, Butter, Wool from New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government announced
here today that it has decided to stop purchasing meat, butter
and wool from New Zealand due to Wellington's negative diplomatic
move.
</P>
<P>
Gholamreza Forouzesh, Minister of Construction Jihad said "Iran
had suspended Iran-New Zealand impending agreements for purchasing
meat, butter and wool."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that the measure has been in
response to New Zealand's recalling of its ambassador from
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is now looking for alternative suppliers elsewhere," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Iran seems to take tough line in
dealing with non-EU member states. The move will certainly
affect its relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
All EU member states, except Greece, have decided to recall
their ambassadors from Tehran because of the alleged involvement of
Iranian leadership in a murder case in Germany in
1992. Ambassadors of Germany, Sweden and France have left from
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Other EU ambassadors are expected to leave from Tehran within
a week or 10 days, a western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Berlin court ruled that the top political
leadership in Iran was behind the assassination of Kurdish
opposition leaders in Berlin's Mykonos restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The court gave life imprisonment to one Iranian national
and a Lebanese and sentenced two other Lebanese to long prison
terms on charge of assassinating the four Kurdish dissidents.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government rejected the ruling by the Berlin
court and President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani Friday blasted out
at the Berlin court ruling, terming the court "sinister" and
"disgraceful".
</P>
<P>
The 64-year-old president attacked Germany for "destroying
100-year friendship" with Iran because of baseless verdict by
the Berlin court on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 800 Iranians staged an anti-German demonstrations in
front of German Embassy Friday afternoon in protest against the
verdict by the Berlin court.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators vowed to launch a suicide attack on the
mission if Bonn continues "hostile" policies against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow, Iran will launch a nationwide anti-German
demonstrations. Millions of Iranians and hundreds of political
groupings throughout the country are expected to join the protest
rally to denounce the verdict of the Berlin court on the Mykonos
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
