<HEADLINE> Iran to Recall Ambassadors from European Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government announced
here today that it will recall its ambassadors as a tit-for-tat
measure against European countries in the wake of the Berlin court
verdict.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry stated that the move was meant to
reciprocate the decision of the European governments concerned to
recall their ambassadors from Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the Netherlands,
now rotary head of the European Union (EU), said Saturday that EU
members had recalled their ambassadors from Tehran.
</P>
<P>
But, the report said, Italy and Greece, both EU members,
said Saturday that their ambassadors are still in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the recalling of ambassadors means a
big backtrack in Iran's relations with EU countries though they
do not officially downgrade their diplomatic ties from ambassador
level to the level of charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin verdict will also greatly affect economic and
trade relations between Iran and EU member states, which take
a share of 41.3 percent of Iran's total imports and 32.8
percent of its total export.
</P>
<P>
However, it seems that both sides do not want to break their
relations, with economic and trade links in particular.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided to recall their ambassadors after the Berlin
court verdict which ruled that the top political leadership in
Iran were behind the assassination of four opposition leaders
in a Berlin restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The EU said in its declaration that it condemns the
involvement of the Iranian authorities and regards such behavior
as totally unacceptable international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The EU also decided to suspend the critical dialogue with
the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
All EU member states, except Greece and Italy, have decided
to recall their ambassadors from Tehran. Ambassadors from Germany,
Sweden and France have left from Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Other ambassadors are expected to leave Tehran within a week
or 10 days, a western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammoud Mohammadi, spokesman for Iran's Foreign Ministry,
Friday described as "unprincipled" the stance of the EU president.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the stance is based on unfounded
remarks of the Berlin court verdict and pressure exerted by
those who want to strain Iran-EU relations.
</P>
<P>
He rejected connecting Iran, a country which itself has been a
victim of terrorist acts, with acts of terrorism by some countries
which on occasions have provided safe sanctuary for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran respects international laws and
regulations in its foreign policy and does not allow the
critical dialogue with EU to be used a pressure lever against
Iran," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Based on its principled policy and goodwill, Iran has
welcomed the critical dialogue with EU in the past years with the
aim that both sides could openly raise their criticism," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But unfortunately, Iran has always been a witness to biased
provocations and sabotage of some of the members," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Germany have recalled their ambassadors from each
other's capitals. Each of the two has also expelled four diplomats
of the other from its capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0029 </DOCNO>
