<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Targets Economic Growth at 6.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has cherished an aim to boost
its economic growth to 6.2 percent for the fiscal year 1997-98
from 5.7 percent in the previous fiscal year, the Egyptian Gazette
reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Ministerial Economic Group Saturday,
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal al-Ganzouri laid out the blueprint
for the nation and called for extensive efforts to attract huge
investments for the fiscal 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
"The targeted economic growth rate will be 6.2 percent," said
Ganzouri after he presented the Cabinet-proposed annual budget to
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget will be submitted to the People's Assembly for
discussion before May.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri said he expected that 58 billion Egyptian pounds
(about 17 billion U.S. dollars) will be invested in Egypt during
the first year to help reduce the level of unemployment through
creating more jobs.
</P>
<P>
The lion's share of the sum will come from the private sector,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the prime minister pointed out that there would be no
new duties or burdens to be levied in 1997-98, as the government
declared before. Thus, the ratio of tax to the gross national
income will fall to 17 percent from 18 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt plans to scale up the volume of its general budget for
the coming fiscal year to 84 billion pounds (24.71 billion
dollars) from 77.5 billion (22.79 billion dollars) last year, a
hike of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
To give social services a better care, special expenditure
would rise from 25 percent of the general expenditure last year to
26 percent in the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The budget will secure the natural increase in salaries, take
care of current expenditure for replacement and maintenance to
improve the quality of services, especially in the domains of
education and health.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a landmark blueprint for Egypt's future
development over the next 20 years details plans to speed up the
economic development to achieve an annual growth rate of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Achieving the goals will require 100 billion pounds (about 34
billion dollars) in annual investments over the next 20 years, and
the private sector is planned to shoulder 75 to 80 percent
of the costs for all projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
