<HEADLINE> Zairian Rebels Capture Two More Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zairian rebels of Laurent-Desire
Kabila today captured Kananga, the capital of the Western Kasai
region in south-central Zaire, days after they took Lubumbashi,
the second largest city and "economic lung" of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The rebels today also took Kolwezi, a city in the region of
Shaba in southern Zaire, said official sources in the Zairian
capital.
</P>
<P>
Zairian government troops usually looted the city they would
abandon and flee without a fight. Only in Lubumbashi did the
rebels meet stiff resistance from the elite Special Presidential
Division of the Zairian army.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebel leader Kabila indicated today that he
would "travel very soon, probably to South Africa to dynamize"
the peace negotiation with the Zairian government.
</P>
<P>
"He will travel to have very important meetings," said the
"foreign minister" of the rebels, Bizima Karaha, in Goma in
eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
He said that if necessary, Kabila would meet with President
Mobutu Sese Seko, although to force Mobutu to step down remains
the ultimate goal of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The "foreign minister" also reaffirmed rebels' position of
"Never a ceasefire before talks."
</P>
<P>
In another development, Zairian Vice Minister of the Interior,
Lumuna NDubu today announced that troops will be deployed in the
streets of Kinshasa on Monday to foil an attempt by the radical
opposition to stage a "dead city" day.
</P>
<P>
"The soldiers will be deployed in the streets to ensure the
security of the people," said Lumuna on television.
</P>
<P>
He justified the measure by citing the state of emergency
declared by President Mobutu last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The attitude of the government toward the organizers of this
day is negative," said the vice minister, saying that the strike
would not "benefit the people who need to live day from day."
</P>
<P>
The Union for the Democracy and Social Progress, led by Etienne
Tshisekedi who was sacked by Mobutu one week after being nominated
prime minister, launched an appeal for "dead city" and "dead
country" day on Monday to pressure Mobutu to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
