<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq Sign 2 Medicine Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today concluded two accords
with Iraq on supplying the sanctions-stricken country with more
much-needed medicines in accordance with the U.N. oil-for-food
plan, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed by the Iraqi Health Ministry and the
Egyptian International Company for Pharmaceutical Industries, will
be referred to the U.N. Sanctions Committee for ratification in the
next couple of days, said the Egyptian Trade Center in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The agreements came exactly a week after Egypt kicked off a
Medicine Week in Baghdad to cash in on Iraq's dire need for
medicine after six years of suffering under the international
embargo imposed for its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The exhibited drugs from 20 Egyptian firms will be later
offered to the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in late January, Egypt will export 3
million U.S. dollars of medicines to Iraq. The first batch of the
medicine has already reached Iraq in late February.
</P>
<P>
Egypt expects the volume of exports to Iraq to reach 100
million dollars in the first six months of the implementation of
the oil-for-food deal concluded by the U.N. and Iraq last year to
ease the impact of the trade sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
