<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two-time Japanese Olympic Medalist Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese two-time Olympic pole
vault silver medalist Shuhei Nishida died of heart attack at a
Tokyo hospital Sunday night. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
Nishida won his first Olympic silver medal in the 1932 Los
Angeles Games with a Japanese record of 4.30 meters, just one
centimeter off American gold medalist William Miller.
</P>
<P>
Nishida took his second silver in the 1936 Berlin Olympics by
vaulting 4.25 meters, edged by Earle Meadows of the United States
who set an Olympic record of 4.35 meters.
</P>
<P>
After the end of World War II, Nishida served as national
athletic team manager and was in charge of the Japanese Amateur
Athletic Federation in the 1950s and 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
