<HEADLINE> Iranian President Urged to Re-Examination of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today was urged by 15 members of parliament to
re-examine the relations between Bonn and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest response from the parliament after
Thursday's verdict of the Berlin court charging top Iranian
leaders with ordering the 1992 killing of four Kurdish
opposition leaders in Berlin's Mykonos restaurant.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the Iranian
parliament held closed session this morning to review the court
ruling and statements by the prosecutor of the Berlin court
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
The session was held in the presence of Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati. The members of the Foreign Policy Commission of
the Parliament will also meet shortly to discuss and debate the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Anti-German demonstrations took place here today with tens of
thousands of people turning out to protest the Berlin court
verdict. Similar demonstrations were held in 10 other Iranian
cities.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators urged the Iranian government to sever
diplomatic relations and economic ties between Bonn and Tehran,
and to prosecute German firms which provide chemical weapons to
Iraq in the Iranian-Iraqi war between 1980-1988.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour demonstrations in the downtown here sparked the
maximum tensions in the ties between Tehran and Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Germany have already recalled their ambassadors from
each capital and expelled four diplomats from the each side
shortly after the verdict was announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin verdict may also affect economic and trade relations
between Iran and member states of the European Union, which take
a share of 41.3 percent of Iran's total imports and 32.8 percent
of the total export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
