<HEADLINE> Ross Due Back to Mideast on Trouble-Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross is
due back to the Middle East at end of the week on another
trouble-shooting mission aimed at breaking the impasse in the
Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
The message of Ross' return was conveyed today to Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy by U.S. Ambassador to Tel Aviv
Martin Indyk, the Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
This will be Ross' second trip to the region in several weeks
since the Israeli-Palestinian peace process grounded to a halt
due to Israel's start of building the controversial Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem and the March 21 suicide bombing in
Tel Aviv that killed three Israeli women.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Ross traveled to Morocco to hold talks with
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
before heading for Israel to meet with Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu. But he returned empty-handed after failing
to bridge the big gap between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Following Ross' previous trip, U.S. President Bill Clinton
invited Netanyahu to Washington early in the month in an attempt
to press him to make concessions in order to resume the peace
process. But the meeting produced no tangible results as
Netanyahu insisted on his tough stand.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
met with visiting Chief Palestinian Negotiator Saeb Erekat,
Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and PNA Minister of
Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi to learn the Palestinian position
on resuming the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department said that the Clinton administration
was formulating a plan of action as what to do next to get the
Israeli-Palestinian peace march back on track following intensive
consultations with both sides.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Albright herself will also visit the
region soon following Ross's mission so as to solve the deepening
crisis in the deadlocked process.
</P>
<P>
The sticking point in bring the Israelis and Palestinians
back to talks again is that both sides have marked their own red
line on resuming the talks. Israel conditions the resumption of
talks on the PNA's commitment to launching a long-term crackdown
on Palestinian extremist militant groups, while the PNA insists
on Israel's freezing the construction of settlements in East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
