<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on HK Residents' Nationalities and Right of abode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Hong Kong and
Macao Affairs Office of the State Council today gave a detailed
account of the policies regarding Hong Kong residents' nationalities
and the right of abode.
</P>
<P>
During his recent visit to Hong Kong, Wang Fengchao, deputy
director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State
Council, elaborated the principle on the settlement of Hong
Kong residents' nationalities and the right to abide after July 1.
</P>
<P>
These policies formulated by the state is well received by Hong
Kong residents, but also raised some issues unclear to them, which
prompted the spokesman to explain these policies today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that on July 1, China's Nationality Law and
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
will come into force in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress explained issues related to the implementation of the
Nationality Law last May.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong SAR put
forward specific opinions on the implementation of Article 24 of
the Basic Law, thus laying a foundation for the government of the
Hong Kong SAR to formulate ordinances for coming in and going out
of Hong Kong, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
After clarifying the requirements for the Chinese and
non-Chinese citizens, the spokesman stressed that Chinese citizens
will acquire the right of abode in Hong Kong according to the
stipulations of the Basic Law relevant to Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
The non-Chinese citizens including those who have obtained
approval to change their nationalities will acquire the right of
abode in Hong Kong according to the stipulations of the Basic Law
concerning the requirements for the non-Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also explained six categories of permanent Hong
Kong residents can enjoy the right of abode in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
