<HEADLINE> 46 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Forty-six rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in the operations
launched by the Turkish security forces in southeastern Turkey
over the last two days, an official statement said today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the office of the Emergency
Regional Rule, said that the Turkish government troops wiped out
33 PKK guerrillas in Cemisgezek town of Tunceli province, 10
near the Dogankavak village in Besiri town and the Palamut
village in Hasankeyf town of Batman province, two near
Yesilbudak border police station in Baskale town of Van province
linking Iran and one in Uzumlu village in Eruh town of Siirt
province.
</P>
<P>
The security forces also captured one PKK militant in Hizan
town of Bitlis province and seized some weapons and equipment in
the operations, it said.
</P>
<P>
More than 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the PKK started a separatist war in the east and
southeast of the country for self-rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
