<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Young People Prefer Study to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- More Chinese young people become
students than employees as they began to realize the importance of
education in an increasingly competitive society.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics released by the State Statistics Bureau (SSB)
showed that the employment rate among people aged between 15 and
24 decreased to 65.2 percent in 1996 from 81.26 percent in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more people from the same age group attended various
schools for further training. The rate for those who became
students increased to 20.5 percent last year from 14.65 percent in
1982.
</P>
<P>
SSB analysis said that China's rapid economic growth brought
the focus of market competition to personnel. The quality of labor
forces, especially their educational background, has become a
bigger factor for job hunters.
</P>
<P>
The dropped employment rate for young people showed that
Chinese youth who have been aware of the competition are looking
forward to improving their marketability.
</P>
<P>
Rural young people seemed to be more sensitive about the
change. The rate of rural youth going to school increased by 3.77
percentage points in 1995 compared to 1990 while the rate grew by
1.5 percentage points for urban youth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
