<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Holds Nation-wide Anti-German Demonstrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran today launched a nationwide
anti-German demonstrations to protest the Berlin court verdict
charging Iranian top leaders of involvement in murdering Kurdish
opposition leaders in Germany in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Demonstrators turning out in the capital
urged the Iranian government to sever diplomatic relations and
economic ties between Bonn and Tehran, to prosecute German firms
which provide chemical weapons to Iraq during the war with Iran
between 1980 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour demonstrations in in front of the German embassy
and streets in the down town sparked the maximum tensions in the
ties between Tehran and Bonn while the Iranian Parliament was
examining the latest situation in close door session.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the announcement of the Berlin court verdict on
Thursday, Iran and Germany have already recalled their
ambassadors and kicked out four diplomats from the each side.
</P>
<P>
Taking part in the rally were clergymen, students, government
employees, merchants, soldiers and politicians. However, some
people said that they were asked to leave the office and came for
the anti-German demonstrations in front the German Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Holding large pictures of chemical weapon victims and big
portraits of Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei and President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, demonstrators chanted slogans "Down
with Fascist Germany", "Down with USA" and "Down with Israel".
</P>
<P>
While condemning the verdict of the Berlin court,
demonstrators also shouted slogans "the Mykonos trial is
U.S. Plot", "Verdict is disgrace for Westerners,
especially Germans", "German firms must be prosecuted in Iran".
</P>
<P>
There was a heavy police presence in streets nearby and along
the route where the protesters were moving. The police had to cut
off the main street in front the German Embassy, which remained
closed with heavy curtain on the windows.
</P>
<P>
The embassy was under tight security with about 800 anti-riot
policemen stationed in front of the building.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous policeman told Xinhua that anti-riot policemen
were ordered to maintain the security in front of the embassy in
case of any violence.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to see again what happened to the U.S. embassy
18 years ago," the policemen said, referring to the taken-over of
the U.S. embassy by Iranian students right after the Islamic
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Reza Akrami, member of Parliament Board of Directors and the
Parliament Foreign Relations Committee, made a long speech,
condemning the Berlin court ruling, claiming that the verdict has
no legal value.
</P>
<P>
A resolution was issued at the end of the demonstration,
calling on the government to firmly and resolutely react to the
German government and all other countries which pursue the
anti-Iran policy.
</P>
<P>
Some university students termed the Berlin court's proceedings
as a pre-meditated scenario designed directly by the United
States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rahman Housseini, a law student at the Tehran University, said
the proceedings of the German court was a political one rather
than judicial.
</P>
<P>
Similar demonstrations were also held in other ten cities in
Iran, including Arak, Qom, Tabriz, Ardabil and Shahr Kord.
</P>
</TEXT>
