<HEADLINE> Ancient City Builds Modern Transport Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Quanzhou, an ancient trade hub in
east China's Fujian province, has given priority to building
modern transport facilities as the foundation for its development.
</P>
<P>
Quanzhou was one of the largest ports in the world back in the
Song and Yuan dynasties (10th to 14th centuries).
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, Quanzhou has expanded the handling capacity
of its port to 13 million tons each year and opened ocean shipping
lines to more than 20 countries and regions. Last year, the
Quanzhou port handled eight million tons of cargos, ranking 18th
in China.
</P>
<P>
The city has invested more than two billion yuan in building
and upgrading nearly 1,000 km of highways over the past four
years, and an expressway connecting Quanzhou with Xiamen, another
major port in the area, will open to traffic in the coming
September.
</P>
<P>
It has renovated the former military Jinjiang airport to
accommodate large and medium-sized passenger planes. Since the
renovated airport opened at the end of last year, the number of
air routes between Quanzhou and other cities has increased from
five to 11, with 48 flights each week.
</P>
<P>
The airport has so far handled more than 50,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
Quanzhou is also building its first railway, connecting
Zhangping in western Fujian to Xiaoxi in Quanzhou. Some 127 km of
tracks have been laid. The railway is scheduled to go into
operation within the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
