<HEADLINE> Pinto Wins London Marathon with New Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Portugal's Antonio Pinto chalked
up the men's title with a new course record at the London Marathon
race on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old fomer professional cyclist, title-winner in
1992, crossed the finish-line with a time of two hours seven
minutes and 55 seconds, also his personal best.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Stefano Baldini came second with 2:07:57.3, followed by
Olympic champion Josiah Thugwane of South Africa in 2:08:06.4.
</P>
<P>
In the women's sections, Briton Liz McColgan's bid to win a
second successive London Marathon was dashed by her closest rival
Kenyan Joyce Chepchumba in the final 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion McColgan, 32, took the lead from the
beginning and seemed she could repeat last year's triumph, but
Chepchumba produced a surprising late spurt to just edge in front
by clocking two hours 26 minutes and 51 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chepchumba has changed the clash record against McColgan. The
Kenyan had to settle for the second behind McColgan 12 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
McColgan and Lidia Simon of Romania finished second and third
here with 2:26:52.3 and 2:27:11.4 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
