<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Strives to Become China's Petrochemical Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province has
been expanding its petrochemical industry by making systematic use
of its rich offshore oil and gas resources.
</P>
<P>
The South China Sea, which surrounds Hainan, is said to have
58,000 billion cu m of natural gas reserves and 29.2 billion tons
of oil reserves in its vast two million sq km of sea areas.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the island province has decided to
treat the petrochemical industry as a pillar for economic
development and plans to develop petrochemical industrial sector
and construct large petrochemical plants mainly engaged in deep
oil refining on the western coast in the coming ten years.
</P>
<P>
While making good use of the cheap and easily-obtained natural
gas as raw material, the province will also expand the chemical
industry by building gas fertilizer production bases and
comprehensive chemical factories, and advance deep processing
industries featuring the production of high-value-added products
such as plastics and synthetic fiber out of materials made by the
oil and gas chemical plants.
</P>
<P>
Hainan's plan has been implemented since the construction of an
offshore gas and chemical project in Yangpu Economic Development
Zone on the island was approved by the central government in early
March.
</P>
<P>
The project, China's largest of its kind and expected to cost
15.5 billion yuan, will include the exploration of the Orient 1-1
Gas field, construction of two sets of equipment capable of
producing 450,000 tons of synthetic ammonia, and 800,000 tons of
urea annually in Yangpu, and installation of a gas pipeline on
land.
</P>
<P>
The Orient 1-1 gas field is verified to have 100 billion cu m
of gas reserves, and the annual gas output is estimated at 2.9
billion cu m.
</P>
<P>
Before this, Hainan has started construction of another
chemical fertilizer factory in Dongfang City with the approval of
the central government.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase construction of the factory, which will use gas
from Ya13-1 of the Yinggehai Oilfield as raw material, has been
completed, with equipment producing 300,000 tons of synthetic
ammonia and 520,000 tons of urea a year.
</P>
<P>
Ya13-1 gas field is also proved to have 100 billion cu m of gas
reserves and is reported to be able to produce 3.4 billion cu m of
gas a year.
</P>
<P>
Preparations have been made for the second-stage construction
of the factory, which will involve the building of the equipment
for producing 450,000 tons of synthetic ammonia and 800,000 tons
of urea annually.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Hebang Oil Refinery in Lingao County on the
west coast, with an production capacity of six million tons, has
also been accelerated, coupled with the preparatory work for
building of some other oil and gas deep refining projects,
including projects backed by Dupont and Baasf in Dongfang City to
produce nylon intermediates, with gas as chief fuel. Construction
on a specialized floating glass project, a wood pulp project, and
a paper-making mill will start in the upcoming two years.
</P>
<P>
The province's annual gas utilization volume will reach four to
five billion cu m in 2000 and rise to 15 billion cu m in 2010, and
the province will thus net 10 billion yuan in industrial output
value in 2000, and 40 billion yuan in industrial output value in
2010, according to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chang Closes to Third Salem Open HK Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Michael Chang was just
one step away from the championship trophy for the third time as
the men's singles final was postponed to Monday due to rain at the
1997 Salem Open Hong Kong tennis Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chang was leading Australia's fifth-seeded Patrick Rafter 6-3,
5-3 when the match was forced to be suspended by umpire and
postponed later by Organizers.
</P>
<P>
The worst case in the area would be for the two to split the
runner-up ranking points and the prize money, tournament Director
Michael Luevano said.
</P>
<P>
Taller and tougher-built Rafter made a flying start in the
opening game, with swift net play and chop shots, forcing Chang
sprawling for saves.
</P>
<P>
The two had one Ace each in the first set but Chang made two
double faults in serves.
</P>
<P>
The second set was much more thrilling as the two tried to
improve their serves and make use of every fault from their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
Chang held serve in all the games and led the seemingly final
one 3-1 before play was suspended.
</P>
<P>
Rafter had four Aces and three double faults in serves in the
set while Chang had two double faults.
</P>
<P>
The third-ranked Chang won the annual Salem Open in 1994 and
1995 and was runner-up to compatriot Pete Sampras in last year's
final.
</P>
<P>
The Chang-Rafter clash is a repeat of the 1994 final, which
came out as Rafter's first defeat in the hands of the
Chinese-American.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, now ranked 43rd in the world, is seeking to revenge
over his four losses so far to Chang, two in 1994, one in 1995 and
one suffered earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Rafter had defeated Chang in Key Biscayne, Florida, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
But the 24-year-old Australian at least did not make the same
mistake this time as four years ago in the Hong Kong event.
</P>
<P>
Rafter ate some contaminated seafood on the eve of the 1994
Salem Open final and fell ill for food poisoning before he
surrendered the title 6-1, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
