<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Increases Investment in Jiangsu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
led all other province-level areas in utilizing 9.8 billion US
dollars of contracted investment from Taiwan by the end of last
year, setting up 6,695 Taiwan-funded enterprises locally.
</P>
<P>
One-tenth of the Taiwan-funded enterprises are wholly owned by
Taiwan business people. More than 40 out of Taiwan's top 100
private enterprises have invested in Jiangsu, one of the most
developed areas in China.
</P>
<P>
Average investment in each Taiwan-funded project added to
Jiangsu last year exceeded three million US dollars, rising five
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The province now has more than 300 Taiwan-funded enterprises
with investment beyond 10 million US dollars each, and 60 with
more than 30 million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of Taiwan-funded enterprises are involved
in technology- and capital-intensive projects covering electronics,
machinery, chemicals, building materials, and optical instruments.
</P>
<P>
Some Taiwan business people show a growing interest in
investing in provincial projects in agriculture and infrastructure
construction such as energy and transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a Profile on China Civil Aviation Flight College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Guanghan is a small city 30 km
south of Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan
Province. But, this little known city is home to China Civil
Aviation Flight College (CAFC), the only higher education
institute to train civilian pilots in China.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four decades, some 7,000 civilian pilots and
4,300 aviation engineering personnel have graduated from the
college, which was formerly the 14th flight school of the Chinese
Air Force set up in 1956, said CAFC President Wang Shixiang.
</P>
<P>
The college, assuming its present name in 1987, has also
trained pilots and air traffic controllers for Vietnam, Japan,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Iran, and Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
Himself a graduate from the college, the president said, "over
90 percent of China's civilian pilots are CAFC graduates,
including some leading officials of the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC), regional administrations, and
major airlines."
</P>
<P>
The college has 96 trainer planes, five training airfields, a
flight simulator center equipped with several Cheyenne and Boeing
737 simulators, and an aircraft engine maintenance training
center.
</P>
<P>
Demand for pilots has kept growing due to China's rapidly
expanding airline industry. Since 1993, CAFC has admitted each
year about 600 students, of which about two thirds will become
civilian pilots, said Wu Yaoyun, an official in charge of student
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
He said 441 students were enrolled into the pilot specialty
last year.
</P>
<P>
The students will study 28 subjects such as aeromechanics,
meteorology, and English during the four years, and undertake 230
hours of flight training, said Zhang Zelong, dean of studies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a Profile on China Civil Aviation Flight College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With increasingly closer contacts between China and the rest of
the world, he added, civilian pilots are required to speak fluent
English. Coursework in English runs through the four years.
</P>
<P>
According to a CAAC plan, pilots on domestic routes must
communicate in English with ground air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
Flight training starts in the third year, including 20 hours on
simulators, 170 hours on elementary trainers, and 50 hours on
advanced ones.
</P>
<P>
Graduates will be presented a college diploma, a bachelor's
degree in engineering, and an airline transport pilot license
(frozen) after passing a test by the CAAC.
</P>
<P>
The license will enable the graduates, upon a certain period of
training in the airline, to become co-pilots on Boeing 737
jetliners.
</P>
<P>
Despite the strong demand for pilot students from CAFC,
President Wang pointed out the college is aware of coming
challenges.
</P>
<P>
China Southern Airlines, one of the three leading carriers in
the country, has established its own pilot training base, while
other major airlines may follow suit.
</P>
<P>
To be prepared for the challenges, Wang noted, CAFC seeks to
enhance its competitiveness by reducing its training costs, and
improving the quality of its work.
</P>
<P>
He added the college has also set up a kind of databank
collecting information the performance of graduates in airlines,
so as to be better aware of the carriers' demand on
students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
