<HEADLINE> Australians Share at World Cup Triathlon Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia showed their absolute
dominance at the World Cup Triathlon series opener in Ishigakijima
of Japan, sweeping the men's top two spots as well as the 1-2-3
finish in the women's actions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
World champion Emma Carney got off to a flying start to the
season and won the women's crown, first of the 11-round World Cup
Triathlon series.
</P>
<P>
Carney led an Australian 1-2-3 finish with Rina Hill and Jackie
Gallagher second and third, clocking two hours two minutes five
seconds.
</P>
<P>
She was 13th in the first stage of swimming section in 20:28,
but was the fastest in the bike section with a time of 1:05:25 and
maintained the lead to finish the running section in 36:12.
</P>
<P>
Hill timed 2:03:11 overall and Gallagher 2:04:13.
</P>
<P>
In the men's race, Chris McCormack defeated current world
champion and his compatriot Miles Stewart by 20 seconds in 1:48:12.
</P>
<P>
Jamie Hunt of New Zealand came in third in 1:48:37, only five
seconds slower than Stewart.
</P>
<P>
McCormack was 28th in the swimming and second in the bike, but
his perfect running performance with only 31:38 gave him the final
victory.
</P>
<P>
The winners received 500 points, runners-up 400 and third
placers 350, counting towards the Sydney Olympics in 2000, where
triathlon will make an Olympic debut.
</P>
<P>
The second round will move to Auckland, New Zealand, on April
27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
