<HEADLINE> World Bank to Loan Russia $3 billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
extend Russia a loan of 3 billion U.S. dollars this year to
support its reform of pension system and help fund some housing
and energy-saving projects.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached on Saturday between Russia's First
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov and World Bank President James
David Wolfensohn, who is in Moscow on a visit.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov told reporters on Saturday night that besides reforming
the pension system, the Russian government has also put the
housing sector on this year's agenda for reform.
</P>
<P>
He said that the World Bank chief has also agreed to consider
providing loans for the housing sector reform before the year 2000
as both sides had agreed earlier.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov said that the Russian government has set up a working
team led by Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Sysuyev to maintain close
contact with the World Bank for more funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
