<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt PM Embarks on Trade-Promotion Asian Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri left this morning on a 10-day tour of Malaysia,
Singapore and China in a bid to attract investment and promote
trade.
</P>
<P>
In a statement before his departure at the airport this
morning, he said that the tour is very important as a new step in
Egypt's development process that started in 1982 under the
leadership of President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Sino-Egyptian relations, he said trade and
economic cooperation should grow further to a level compatible to
their deep friendship in the political domain.
</P>
<P>
"My trip to China is designed to expand the scale and scope of
bilateral cooperation on joint ventures and enhance our two-way
trade transactions," he added.
</P>
<P>
"And I believe it could herald a new phase of Sino-Egyptian
economic cooperation," said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and China fell by 9.8 percent to
407.92 million U.S. dollars last year from 452.7 million in 1995,
resulted from a sharp decline in the Egyptian export.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, reviewing the country's economic reforms, which have
been focused on the monetary field, said that they help create
a conducive environment for attracting foreign investment to
develop Egypt's projects.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his Asian trip, Ganzouri reviewed Saturday the
joint projects Egypt wants to have with the three booming
economies in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Egypt will present a number of joint ventures
with these countries for the development of southern Egypt and
implementing infrastructure of giant national projects, covering
cement, fertilizers, natural gas, phosphates and the automobile
industries.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri also presented to President Hosni Mubarak the
agreements expected to be signed during the trip, four with
Malaysia, and five with Singapore and China.
</P>
<P>
The agreements provide for protection of investments,
prevention of dual taxation, activation of trade movement and
implementation of joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
On the trip which is the first by an Egyptian prime minister to
those countries since 1964, the prime minister is accompanied by a
high-level delegation grouping the ministers of electricity,
trade, industry, local administration and cabinet affairs along
with a team of investors and businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
