<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition to Hire Foreign Negotiator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition parties have
resolved to hire an "internationally-recognized professional
negotiator" to assist them towards achieving a single
presidential candidate in the general election to be held this
year.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by opposition parties yesterday in Nyeri
said that a council of elders would be set up to enhance dialogue
between the aspiring presidential hopefuls of opposition parties
in the country.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day meeting, opposition leaders suggested that an
opposition constituent assembly be formed to select the single
candidate should other means fail.
</P>
<P>
If opposition leaders fail to agree on a single candidate
through negotiations, they resolved to employ "a special
strategy" to force a run off between the first two presidential
candidates, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that "participants took note of the
prevailing skepticism and apathy among the people on the slow
progress towards concrete political action in the run-up to the
elections."
</P>
<P>
Last month, six leaders from opposition Ford-Kenya said that
the quest for a single presidential candidate had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
An attempt by 73 members of parliament in 1995 to form the
Opposition Alliance faced competition from a parallel group
fronted by Ford-Asili Chairman Kenneth Matiba and Langata MP
Raila Odinga. 
</P>
