<HEADLINE> Pakistan Denies U.S. Charge on Missile Shipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Saturday denied latest
but often-repeated allegations by Washington about "China's
continuous shipment of M-11 missile components to Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has clarified many times in the past the nature of the
relations with China as well as the kinds of technology transfers,
a Foreign Office spokesman said here.
</P>
<P>
"We did not breach parameters of the Missile Technology Control
Regime (MTCR) or any other international convention law," he said.
</P>
<P>
There was nothing hidden and Pakistan's relationship with
China is "above board," said the spokesman, adding that the two
countries have always remained within the parameters of MTCR.
</P>
<P>
Robert Einhorn, U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State,
claimed on Thursday before the Senate Government Affairs
Sub-committee that China is "suspected of continuing to aid
Pakistan's nuclear weapons program boldly defying protests from
the Clinton administration."  
