<HEADLINE> Solar Cooker Launched to Save Woodlands in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has launched in Kariba,
north Zimbabwe, a solar cooker that might stop the further
destruction of woodlots, local papers reported today.
</P>
<P>
If adopted for use in rural areas, the cooker could help save
trees, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Shaped like a satellite dish, the solar cooker can boil a pint
of water in 10 minutes and it can be used to prepare tea and even
boil eggs.
</P>
<P>
The hand-made machine is currently attracting considerable
people including visitors who pass through the Kariba Information
Centre, where it has been on exhibition until the end of May.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the rural areas use wood as a source of energy,
cutting down a large number of trees every year.
</P>
<P>
The hand-made device costs only 50 US Dollars while a
factory-made cooker fetches up to about 150 dollars, unaffordable
for most households. enditem


