<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Vying to Attract Taiwan Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is working on
regulations and measures to encourage more investment from Taiwan,
according to a senior Beijing municipal government official.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Mayor Lu Yucheng made the remarks at a national trade fair
in Xiamen in east China's Fujian Province. The trade fair, which
opened on April 9, is the country's first special fair targeting
exports to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan-funded enterprises are increasing rapidly in the Chinese
capital, according to Lu. There are now more than 1,600
Taiwan-funded enterprises in Beijing, involving an investment of
1.54 billion US dollars from Taiwan businesses.
</P>
<P>
Lu led a delegation consisting of the Municipal Taiwan Affairs
Office, Trade and Economic Cooperation Committee, and Forestry and
Agricultural Department. It is the first time that the Beijing
Municipal Government organized a delegation to attend trade fairs
outside the capital city.
</P>
<P>
As to the attraction and use of Taiwan funds, Lu said, Beijing
will focus on hi-tech industry, tertiary industry, modern
agriculture, and key industrial sectors and products.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will try to improve its investment environment and
create still better conditions for the Taiwan compatriots,
Vice-Mayor Lu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
