<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indiscriminate Use of Pesticides Reduces Bangladesh's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The indiscriminate use of chemical
fertilizer and pesticides in farmland is lowering Bangladesh's
food production, particularly the high yielding variety (HYV)
rice, according to a task force report issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The average output of HYV rice, which was five metric tons per
hectare in 1969-1970, fell to 3.5 metric tons during the last five
years and the downward trend was continuing, according to the
report of the Bangladesh Institute of Development and Studies
(BIDS).
</P>
<P>
The report quoted BIDS experts as saying that the farmers are
indiscriminately using chemical fertilizer and pesticides in the
cultivable land, which is the main cause of reduced per acre
yield.
</P>
<P>
The report said the use of nitrogen, phosphorous and potassium
in the cultivable land is highly disproportionate to soil
fertility, leading to declines in crop production, it said.
</P>
<P>
Although the use of nitrogen is increasing gradually in the
cultivable land, the comparative use of phosphorous and potassium
is dropping.
</P>
<P>
This has deteriorated the whole agricultural situation,
creating hindrances to attaining food self-sufficiency in
Bangladesh by the year 2000, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
