<HEADLINE> 6,000 Thai Babies Infected With HIV: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- As many as 6,000 babies in
Thailand have the Human Immuno-Deficiency Virus (HIV), who have
contracted the deadly virus from their mothers, according to a
senior public health ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Prakrom Wuthipong, director of the Public Health Department,
said on Saturday that nationwide almost 1 million people are
infected with the virus, which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has a population of 60 million.
</P>
<P>
Prakrom laid much of the blame on the sexual behavior of the
country's men.
</P>
<P>
He said most HIV-positive infants survive until about five or
six years of age, depending on their physical health.
</P>
<P>
There are three stages when babies are at risk of contracting
the disease from their mothers: during pregnancy, during delivery
and through breast-feeding, according to Prakrom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
