<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Construction of Asia's Biggest Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China has sped up the second-phase
construction of Dalate Power Plant in its northern Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The power plant, one of the sources that provide Beijing with
electric power supply, could be be built into a station with a
combined generating capacity of five million kw, replacing Japan's
Kagoshima Power Plant, with a generating capacity of 4.6 million
kw, as Asia's biggest powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the plant has every advantage for
becoming a super-large thermal power station, with easy and plenty
supplies of water, coal, and easy accesses to transportation.
</P>
<P>
Two power-generating units, each with a capacity of 330,000 kw,
were installed for first-phase construction and started generating
electricity in 1995 and in 1996. By the end of February, the two
units had generated a total of 2.73 billion kw/hours of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
For second-stage construction, which is now under way, the
power plant will be added with the installation of two more
generating units of the same capacity.
</P>
<P>
The No.3 generating unit is scheduled to be installed and start
operation in later December this year and the No.4 unit will be
installed and go into operation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Engineers and officials with the power plant have been making
preparations for the third-phase construction and hope to kick off
the construction in 1998 and finish it in the year 2000, according
to sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
