<HEADLINE> More Students Equipped with Pagers at College Compuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The sound of beeping can be heard
occasionally in academic lectures as paging business has become
brisk on China's university campuses.
</P>
<P>
An article in today's China Daily "Business Weekly" reported
that Yang Hengda, a professor with the People's University, is
sometimes interfered by pagers during his two-hour lectures.
</P>
<P>
However, Yang does not blame his students. "I know many of them
carry beepers for job-hunting," he said.
</P>
<P>
Present-day China's universities, which are gradually
decreasing their job-finding functions for graduates, have
inherited the role from the central economic planning era. So
graduate students have to find jobs by themselves today.
</P>
<P>
A new round of job-hunting began last autumn when the class of
1997 began distributing their resumes and job applications
through the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the spring semester, feedback from
government departments, companies and other institutions for
further exams and interviews began coming back to the schools,
which drove many students to find effective communication means to
make sure potential employers can contract them directly and
swiftly.
</P>
<P>
College dormitory rooms do not have phones. The only one or two
lobby telephones are always busy with students calling out, which
prompted many to buy pagers.
</P>
<P>
"Each beep may mean an opportunity," said Guo Jie, a senior at
Beijing Language and Culture University. That opinion made half
of Guo's 30 classmates buy pagers.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yang, who will graduate this year from People's University,
said just seven of the 38 people in his class do not carry pagers.
</P>
<P>
Pager stores in Beijing's Di'anmen reported their campus
customers rose sharply this spring. Some pager businessmen,
seeing the potential market, took initiative to attractive more
students.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, Best Pager Service Company in Beijing has
launched several promotions at universities, where it offered ten
percent discounts on beepers.
</P>
<P>
Some companies leased pagers to students at one yuan per day,
which also attracted some university customers.
</P>
<P>
Pagers have been seen on campus since they became a fashion
accessory for Chinese business people in late 1980s. But before
1990, only the students involved in business bought them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
