<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Warns Against "Pouring Oil Into Fire" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today called on all parties concerned not to "pour oil into the
fire" after German-Iranian relations turned strained following the
so-called "Mykonos" trial in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Welt am Sonntag,
Kinkel said Germany does not want to rupture its relations with
Iran which have lasted more than a hundred years.
</P>
<P>
The most silly thing would be to conduct a "war of cultures,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first formal comment by Kinkel after the court
verdict in Berlin Thursday against four men involved in the murder
of four Kurdish opposition figures in the Mykonos restaurant in
Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court said Iranian leaders ordered the killings of
Sadegh Charafkandi, chief of the outlawed Democratic Kurdish Party
in Iran, and his three aides in 1992, a charge rejected by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Following that, both Germany and Iran have recalled their
ambassadors and expelled four diplomats from each other's capitals.
</P>
<P>
The European Union also reacted with a mass recall of
ambassadors and suspension of dialogues with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel noted that he had in the past supported political
dialogues with those Iranians also in favor of dialogues.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue which Bonn had pursued with Tehran remained
suspended for the moment, he said, stressing that a dialogue could
not be conducted at any costs.
</P>
<P>
The limit was reached when international law and the
sovereignty of another country were massively violated, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also said foreign ministers of the European Union states
will meet on April 29 in Luxembourg to review relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
A "revaluation" of German and European policies toward Iran was
necessary at the moment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Germany's top industry organization earlier also appealed that
German-Iran business ties not be impaired despite the tensions
after the "Mykonos" trial in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The German Council of Trade and Industry (DIHT), the umbrella
organization of the chambers of commerce, said Friday that it was
advising German companies to maintain their business ties with
Iran and not to let themselves be drawn into political issues.
</P>
<P>
It also said that a visit by a delegation of major business
people from Tehran to Germany will still go ahead as scheduled on
April 21-25.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian delegation, consisting of 26 representatives of
various chambers representing different industrial sectors, is
expected to visit Dresden and Hamburg before meeting German
colleagues at DIHT headquarters in Bonn on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Germany is currently Iran's biggest trade partner in Europe,
with its exports to Iran last year amounting to 2.2 billion marks
(about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars) and imports from Iran 1.1 billion
marks (about 650 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
