<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Cases in Jakarta May be 32,400 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of HIV/AIDS carriers
in Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, may have reached a record high
of 32,400, but the government now puts the figure at only 162 --
101 HIV cases and 61 AIDS cases, an official said.
</P>
<P>
"The figure is based on reports from hospitals in Jakarta.
There are many HIV/AIDS cases left undetected and their number may
reach as high as 200 times of the reported cases," Jakarta deputy
governor Rs. Museno said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed deep concern over the increasing number of
HIV/AIDS cases and called for a breakthrough in preventing
HIV/AIDS from spreading further, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The deputy governor said the way Jakarta residents have sexual
intercourse with illicit partners is responsible for the spread of
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS in Jakarta was first detected in 1987. In the next 10
years, the number of the cases increased to 162, with 61 of them
having developed AIDS and 36 died.
</P>
<P>
The current figure shows that 80 percent of HIV/AIDS carriers
are of productive age.
</P>
<P>
Up to February 1997, there were reported 517 HIV/AIDS carriers
in Indonesia, 393 of whom were infected with HIV and 124 developed
AIDS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
