<HEADLINE> U.S. Company to Drill More Oil, Gas in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Atlantic Richfields Oil
Company (ARCO) of the United States has started work again to
conduct more oil and natural gas drilling off Myanmar's coast
after carrying out a seismic survey with the state-run Myanmar Oil
and Gas Enterprise (MOGE).
</P>
<P>
According to today's official newspaper New Light of Myanmar,
the drilling is being conducted at the Shwepiyaye test well, the
second well at Block M-9 off Mottama coast, as good prospects are
found to get oil and natural gas there.
</P>
<P>
The first test well -- the Shwepyithay at the same block, which
was drilled by the ARCO in February, was able to yield natural gas
on commercial scale one month later after the Yadana and the
Yetagun fields off the same coast.
</P>
<P>
The Shwepyiaye test well, which is located at about 260 km
south of Yangon, Myanmar's capital, will be drilled down to 3.15
km, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company signed a production sharing contract with the
MOGE in July 1995 for exploration of oil and natural gas at the
block.
</P>
<P>
Exploration is also being done at another block, which is M-7,
by the U.S. company under its second contract reached with the
MOGE last May.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Myanmar has signed over 20
production sharing contracts with oil companies from nearly 10
countries including Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia, Thailand and the United States, and foreign investment
in the oil and gas sector had reached 2.13 billion U.S. dollars in
34 permitted projects by the end of February this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
