<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Face Competition for Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's personal savings deposits
are expected to grow steadily despite intense challenges from the
domestic capital market, said a senior economist.
</P>
<P>
Xu Hongyuan of the State Planning Commission's Information
Center told the Beijing-based China Daily that personal savings
would increase to 4,700 billion yuan by the end of the year from
3,850 billion yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase would be good news for China's banks, which
consider personal deposits as major fund sources. Stability of
the banking sector, which provides more than 90 percent of the
State enterprises' working capital, is crucial for the country's
economic situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rise expected in savings deposits, Xu noted, the
pace would be slower than last year because of competition from
treasury bonds, stocks, corporate bonds and anticipated industrial
investment funds.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of the capital market this year would be the major
negative factor for the deposits' growth, which Xu predicted at
22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance has decided to issue 123 billion yuan
in voucher treasury bonds this year, four times more than last
year's issue of such T-bonds.
</P>
<P>
The voucher bonds are similar to bank deposits but have higher
yields than deposits. They are expected to be bought by individual
investors.
</P>
<P>
The stock market also is attracting more investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
