<HEADLINE> Italy's Jews Urge Resumption of Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Up to 300 Jewish celebrities in
Italy appealed today for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to resume the peace talks with the Palestinians as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to the Israeli leader, who arrived here
Friday for an economic conference, they said that three years
after the signing of the Oslo peace accord, all sides concerned
should try to avoid the danger that violence could degenerate into
new conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo Agreements, signed in 1993 between Israel and
the Palestinians, issues such as the status of Jerusalem and
Jewish settlements were to be resolved in final-stage
negotiations, before which neither side should take unilateral
action to change the present situation.
</P>
<P>
But in mid-March, Israel decided to set up new Jewish
settlements in the Arab East Jerusalem, evoking new conflicts
between the Palestinians and Israelis. So far 12 people have been
killed and several hundred others injured in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
East Jerusalem was occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
war and was later annexed by Israel as its united capital. The
Israeli move was not universally acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish community in Italy also urged Israel and the
Palestinians to "renew joint action to stop terrorism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
