<HEADLINE> Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted the second
fastest growth rate in exports between 1990 and 1996, according to
a survey by the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
In its 1996 survey of global trade performance, the WTO said
the Philippines' annual average export growth of 17 percent
between 1990 and 1996 was second only to Malaysia, local press
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's exports grew by an annual average of 18 percent
during the period. China and Thailand were tied in third place
with an annual average export growth of 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines exceeded by 10 percentage points the world
average of seven percent, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is expecting the country's exports to
hit an all-time high of 63.7 billion US dollars by 1998 with an
annual export growth average of 25 percent from 1996 to 1998, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
It said the Ramos government has worked out several strategies
to strengthen the country's exports, including continuing to
enhance export winners and promote new products that have
comparative advantages.  
</P>
</TEXT>
