<HEADLINE> Fujimori: Peru to Quit Andean Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- President Alberto Fujimori has
announced that Peru will leave the Andean Group, media reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech last night at a meeting in the Peruvian College of
Economists, Fujimori accused the Andean Pact trade group of
working with plans that limit free and fair trade.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of the Andean Group member countries met on
April 10 in Santafe de Bogota, Colombia, but failed to agree on
Peru's return to the Andean Group.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said in his speech that the main purpose of Peru to be
in the Andean Group was to develop the productive apparatus and to
create employment, but that those targets cannot be reached if the
Andean Group continues working with the present system.
</P>
<P>
"Peru has insisted on the need of renewing the Andean Group
through the approval of a set of rules related to the origin of
the products, the elimination of subsidies, and other measures
aimed to generate a free and fair trade in the subregion," he said.
</P>
<P>
On March 9, the presidents of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru
and Venezuela approved the creation of an Andean Community
economic bloc to replace the ailing 26-year-old Andean Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
