<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Industry Drives Changchun's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Changchun, capital of northeast
China's Jilin Province, is resolved to become China's auto
industrial production center, according to an article in today's
"Business Weekly".
</P>
<P>
Mi Fengjun, the city's party secretary-general, is quoted as
saying that assembly and parts plants have generated half of the
city's industrial output in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Changchun makes one fourth of China's cars, one third of its
trains and one tenth of its tractors.
</P>
<P>
The Changchun-based China First Automotive Corporation, the
oldest and largest truck and sedan production base established in
1953, is driving growth of the city's 178 assembly and parts
plants. These enterprises generated two billion yuan (240 million
US dollars) in output value from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mi said they would continue to play up auto industry by
encouraging cooperation with important international companies.
</P>
<P>
The city has now 1,108 joint ventures, involving a total
investment of 392 million U.S. dollars, he noted. From 1991 to
1995, the city's auto enterprises set up 18 joint ventures with
foreign conglomerates from Germany, Malaysia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Mi went on to say that joint ventures brought in capital and
advanced technology and management to the city's auto industry.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation with international companies in the auto industry
-- especially parts makers -- will be reinforced," said Mi, adding
cooperation will focus on radial tires, vehicle refitting and
vehicle electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Auto industry has revitalized the city's four development
zones, including two focusing on high-tech industries, one
specializing in auto trade and one in tourism.
</P>
<P>
Mi noted that they will encourage overseas investment in
projects involving infrastructure, agriculture, resource
utilization and revitalization of state enterprises this year.
</P>
<P>
Changchun is one of China's oldest industrial bases, and state
enterprises own 75 percent of the city's industrial assets, which
makes it hard to revitalize state enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
