<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Denounces Campaign Against Bananas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica has denounced what it
calls a campaign against the fruit in Europe that has caused a
drop in the country's banana exports.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfair to charge Costa Rica with exporting bananas with
an excess of pesticides, of maltreating the workers in the banana
plantations, and of polluting the environment, because the facts
reveal a completely different situation," Agriculture and
Livestock Minister Ricardo Garron said.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's banana exports dropped 9.7 percent in the first
two months of this year, from 95.3 million U.S. dollars in
February of 1996, to 86.09 million dollars in the same month of
1997, said the Foreign Trade Ministry in a report published today.
</P>
<P>
Garron said that the slander campaign against bananas harvested
in Costa Rica, the world's second largest banana producer after
Ecuador, does not make any sense.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica banana-cultivated area was 49,000 hectares in 1996,
5.4 percent less than in 1995, according to the National Banana
Corporation (Corbana).
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican bananas are sold in the United States, Germany,
Belgium, and Italy. 
</P>
