<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (19-20) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (19-20)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What are the two categories of Hong Kong residents,
and what are the qualifications for permanent Hong Kong residency?
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to Article 24 of the Basic Law, residents of
the Hong Kong SAR include permanent residents and non-permanent
residents.
</P>
<P>
Permanent residents of the Hong Kong SAR are:
</P>
<P>
(1) Chinese citizens born in Hong Kong before or after the
establishment of the Hong Kong SAR;
</P>
<P>
(2) Chinese citizens who have ordinarily resided in Hong Kong
for a continuous period of not less than seven years before or
after the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR;
</P>
<P>
(3) Persons of Chinese nationality born outside Hong Kong of
those residents listed in categories (1) and (2);
</P>
<P>
(4) Persons not of Chinese nationality who have entered Hong
Kong with valid travel documents, have ordinarily resided in Hong
Kong for a continuous period of not less than seven years and have
taken Hong Kong as their place of permanent residence before or
after the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR;
</P>
<P>
(5) Persons under 21 years of age born in Hong Kong or those
residents listed in category (4) before or after the establishment
of the Hong Kong SAR;
</P>
<P>
(6) Persons other than those residents listed in categories (1)
to (5), who, before the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR, had
the right of abode in Hong Kong only.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned residents will have the right of abode in
the Hong Kong SAR and be qualified to obtain, in accordance with
the laws of the region, permanent identity cards which state their
right of abode.
</P>
<P>
Question: What is the relationship between a Hong Kong resident
and a Chinese citizen?
</P>
<P>
Article 33 of the Chinese Constitution stipulates, "any person
who has acquired a nationality of the People's Republic of China
is a citizen of the People's Republic of China." Article 2 of the
Nationality Law of the People's Republic of China stipulates, "The
People's Republic of China is a unified multi-ethnic country, and
persons of all ethnicity shall have Chinese nationality." Its
Article 3 stipulates that double nationality of a Chinese citizen
shall not be recognized. In its memorandum to the British
government in 1984, the Chinese government clearly stated, "All
Hong Kong Chinese compatriots, whether or not they hold
the 'British Dependent Territories Citizen's Passport,' are
Chinese citizens." All these stipulations are consistent in
principle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
