<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (19-20) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the Basic Law stipulates, residents of Hong Kong include
Chinese citizens and foreigners. Such a special phenomenon has led
to fairly complicated provisions on the rights of Chinese citizens
in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
First, rights enjoyed by Chinese citizens among Hong Kong
residents are relatively extensive. For instance, they have the
freedom to travel and to enter and leave Hong Kong, the freedom to
move within the Hong Kong SAR, the freedom to emigrate to other
countries and regions, and the freedom to raise a family.
</P>
<P>
Second, according to the Basic Law, only permanent residents of
Hong Kong have the right to vote and stand for election in the
election of the Chief Executive and the legislature. That is to
say, voters are not limited to "Chinese citizens among the
permanent residents."
</P>
<P>
Third, according to the Basic Law, the Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong SAR and its other principal officials should be Chinese
citizens among Hong Kong's permanent residents who have no right
of abode in any foreign country. That is to say, only Chinese
citizens among Hong Kong's permanent residents are eligible to
assume high official positions in the Hong Kong SAR. Article 99 of
the Basic Law stipulates, "public servants serving in all
government departments of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region must be permanent residents of the region, except otherwise
provided for in Article 101 of this law regarding public servants
of foreign nationalities and except for those below a certain rank
as prescribed by law."
</P>
<P>
Fourth, Article 21 of the Basic Law stipulates, "Chinese
citizens who are residents of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region shall be entitled to participate in the management of state
affairs according to law. In accordance with the assigned number
of seats and the selection method specified by the National
People's Congress, Chinese citizens among residents of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region shall locally elect deputies of
the region to the National People's Congress to participate in the
work of the highest organ of state power." Here "Chinese citizens
among Hong Kong residents" is apparently broader than "Chinese
citizens among permanent residents of the Hong Kong SAR" referred
to above.
</P>
<P>
In short, with the application of the "one country, two
systems" policy in Hong Kong and with realities in Hong Kong taken
into account, some complex situations have arisen concerning the
rights of Hong Kong residents and Chinese citizens among them. The
Basic Law has made proper provisions on all relevant issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
