<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Wins Argentine Pole Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Jacques Villeneuve
maintained his winning momentum in this year's Formula One world
championship on Saturday, claiming the pole position for Sunday's
Argentine Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve shattered the old qualifying record by more than six
seconds by lapping in one minute 24.473 seconds in his
Williams-Renault.
</P>
<P>
His team mate Heinz-Harald Frentzen wound up second-quickest to
claim a place alongside the Canadian on the front row of the grid.
</P>
<P>
It was Villeneuve's third pole position of the season, his
fourth in succession, the sixth of his career and the 100th for
Williams.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Olivier Panis in a Prost claimed third place ahead of
double world champion Michael Schumacher of Germany in a
Goodyear-shod Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
The race will be the 600th Formula One world championship event
since the series was inaugurated in 1950. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
