<HEADLINE> Latin American Cultural News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following is a summary of
Latin American cultural news briefs in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine dancer Paloma Herrera will receive
the "Gino Tani" international award in recognition of her
achievements, it was announced earlier this week in Rome, Italy.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The First Science Fiction and Fantasy Cinema
Festival will be held April 30 to May 4 at the World Trade Center
of the Mexican capital, with the participation of 12 films from
Spain, France, Japan, the United States, and Mexico, Myren Gea,
organizer of the festival, said.
</P>
<P>
The festival will be held as part of the activities of the
Comics, Science Fiction and Fantasy III Convention, in which
books, movies, lectures, seminars and other features will be
offered.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- An exhibition of the work of British
artist Henry Moore (1898-1986) will open April 30 in the Colombian
capital.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will present 123 of his works that show the
evolution of his work. The exhibition, sponsored by "The Henry
Moore Foundation" of Britain will also tour several other Latin
American cities.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Grammy 97 award winner Ruben Blades announced he
will take part in the first film completely made in Panama.
</P>
<P>
"I am telling the story of three women, which will be the first
moving picture written, filmed, and directed by Panamanians in
Panama," Blades told the local press.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- South African writer Nadine Gordimer, 1991 Nobel
Literature Prize winner, arrived here for a three-day visit to
Uruguay in her tour of South America that includes Argentina and
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Seven Brazilian films, including "El Pagador de
Promesas," "El Viento y la Ostra," and "El Pequeno Diccionario
Amoroso" will take part in the Cannes Film Festival scheduled for
May 7 to 18 in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
