<DOCNO> XIE19970413.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Conservatives Narrow Points With Labor in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The British ruling Conservative
Party has narrowed considerably the gap with the opposition Labor
Party, according to three opinion polls to be published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An NOP poll for the Sunday Times showed the Conservative Party
is now 20 points behind Labor, up four points from last week and
dealing a severe blow to Labor's hope of wining the May 1
election.
</P>
<P>
A Gallup poll in the Sunday Telegraph showed Labor only enjoys
a 16-point lead over the Conservatives, while a week ago the gap
was 23 percentage points. It was the lowest level recorded by
Gallup since Tony Blair became its leader three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Gallup showed support for Labor at 49 percent, the
Conservatives at 33 percent and the Liberal Democrats at 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
An ICM poll in the Observer also put Labor 16 points ahead of
the Conservatives, but this was unchanged from the previous week.
</P>
<P>
ICM gave Labor 48 percent and the Conservatives 32 percent,
down one point from last week, while the Liberal Democrats were up
one point at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NOP poll also showed the Liberal Democrats gaining against
Labor, showing them up five points to 17 percent, their best NOP
rating since May 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
